"Darkening thy power to lend base subjects light?" - a question that echoes in the halls of time, a query to the Muse that lights the path of the poet's heart.

"Rise, resty Muse, my love's sweet face survey," - an invitation, a plea, a command, all rolled into one. The poet's love, a beacon, a muse, a guiding star.

"By chance or nature's changing course untrimm'd;" - the raw beauty of nature, untouched, unaltered, a testament to the power of chance and time.

"Which, labouring for invention, bear amiss" - the struggle of creation, the burden of innovation, a testament to the artist's plight.

"Where art thou, Muse, that thou forget'st so long" - a cry in the wilderness, a longing for inspiration, a yearning for the Muse's touch.

"And make Time's spoils despised every where." - the ravages of time, the decay of beauty, a lament for what once was.

"Presume not on thy heart when mine is slain;" - a warning, a plea, a statement of vulnerability, the poet's heart laid bare.

"To speak of that which gives thee all thy might?" - a question of power, of source, of origin, a query into the heart of might.

"Is but the seemly raiment of my heart," - a declaration of love, of devotion, of the poet's heart dressed in the finery of affection.

"When in eternal lines to time thou growest:" - a testament to the power of words, of poetry, of the eternal lines that stand the test of time.

"To make some special instant special blest," - a wish, a desire, a longing to make a moment stand out, to make it blessed.

"To this composed wonder of your frame;" - an admiration, a praise, a tribute to the beauty of the beloved, a wonder in every sense.

"Hath been" - a statement of existence, of being, a testament to the power of love, of poetry, of the Muse.
